Ibanez and Steve Vai have been working closely together for more than three decades - with the first JEM guitar being introduced to the world in 1987 - and the PIA (Paradise In Art) lineup represents their latest collaboration, and is arguably their best yet.

This new grip offers a balanced, contemporary design aesthetic, and symbolises a combination of unity, companionship, and interpersonal bonds (apparently).
Not only that, but the tremolo cavity plate on the rear of the guitar is now held in place magnetically, which allows for faster string changes and tremolo system adjustments.
For the body, Ibanez have opted to use Alder, carved in that instantly-familiar 80's-style "Super-Strat" dual-cutaway shape.
Bolted on to the body is a 5-piece Maple and Walnut neck, carved to meet the demands of Vai's fluid playing technique.
In addition to this, the Rosewood fingerboard features scalloped frets from 21 to 24, along with Prestige Fret Edge treatment for a super-smooth playing experience
Based upon Vai's own tonal preferences, the DiMarzio UtoPIA pickups have been designed to offer smoother highs, more scooped mids, and a pronounced low-end.
These pickups bring together this incredible range of tones with beautiful aesthetics and design elements, making them the perfect fit for the PIA's cosmetic features.
Ever since the creation of the first JEM in 1987, Steve Vai guitars have featured the innovative Edge tremolo bridge.
This bridge and its groundbreaking Lion's Claw tremolo cavity allows you to rapidly increase and lower your guitar's pitch without affecting your tuning stability.

With its classic design and construction, powerful humbucker pickups, and gorgeous aesthetics
In 1957, the Gibson Les Paul was first fitted with the Patent-Applied-For (PAF) humbucker pickups, and helped change the landscape of popular music for generations to come.

Originally these pickups utilised AlNico 2 magnets, but by the early 1960s these had been swapped out for the stronger AlNico 5 kind. These new magnets gave a more powerful sound to the pickups, and helped pave the way for future rock and metal music.
These new pickups perfectly complimented the guitar's tonewoods, and led to the creation of the Gibson Les Paul Standard.
To honour those legendary early-60s guitars, Gibson's new Les Paul Standard models see a return to this original Standard design.

Featuring a solid (non-chambered) Mahogany back piece, with an AA Figured Maple top, the natural tone generated by these guitars makes them the ideal centrepiece for any player looking for that vintage Les Paul sound.
In addition to this, the neck is crafted from Solid Mahogany, and features a Slim Taper profile shape, offering a comfortable playing experience whatever your playstyle.
To recreate that powerful, early '60s, AlNico V PAF tone, Gibson have fitted a set of BurstBucker 61 pickups to the new Les Paul Standard.
Whether you want those thick, creamy Neck position tones for a lead line, or those biting Bridge position power chord sounds, this is the guitar for you.

newOverview.overviewBody: The Gibson Les Paul Standard 50s Heritage Cherry Sunburst Guitar once-again brings together all of the exquisite qualities that launched the original Les Paul Standard to stardom.
With its solid Mahogany back (no weight relief!), maple top, PAF-like humbuckers, and traditional Heritage Cherry Sunburst finish, this guitar is like a welcome slice of Gibson history.
Early 1950s Les Paul guitars came equipped with P-90 single coil pickups, but with the invention of the PAF humbucker in 1957, the sonic landscape was changed forever.

PAF pickups were named "humbuckers" due to the fact that they eliminated the unwanted 60 cycle hum normally associated with Single Coils - they literally "bucked the hum". This meant the guitars could now be played at much higher volumes, paving the way for louder and more aggressive musical styles.
As a bonus point, the tones these pickups generated were richer and thicker than a single coil too, perfectly complimenting the nature of a Les Paul guitar.
And so, by 1958 the Les Paul Standard was born.

Part of the original 1950's Les Paul's appeal, even more than six decades after its release, is the rock-solid feel you get from it. This was down to the rounded neck profile, and non-chambered solid mahogany back.
With the new Gibson Les Paul Standard 50s lineup, that particular type of construction is back!
With the solid body and maple top, you get a naturally rich tone with plenty of high-end snap. On top of that, there's a Vintage 50s profile Mahogany neck, that sits comfortably in your hand.
Complimenting the traditional Les Paul Standard build is a set of vintage-voiced BurstBucker pickups, created to invoke the much coveted voice of those original PAF pickups.
With the BurstBucker 1 and BurstBucker 2 combination on this Les Paul Standard guitar, you get one of the closest approximations to this elusive tone yet.
These vintage-sounding pickups offer you the choice between that vintage, creamy neck pickup sound, and the hotter, biting bridge tones.
Each of these pickups has independent Volume and Tone controls, opening up a whole world of vintage voices for you to choose from.

In 1958, the Gibson Les Paul was reintroduced with the now famous sunburst finish.

Today, the Gibson Les Paul is synonymous with rock and roll and has been played by many of the most famous guitarists to ever have lived including Jimmy Page, Keith Richards, Slash and more.
Now, through the incredible dedication of the Gibson Custom Shop team, you can own an incredible recreation of the 1958 Les Paul Standard - the guitar that marked the beginning of the burst.
As a Gibson Custom Shop guitar, the Gibson 1958 Les Paul Standard Reissue represents the best of guitar build quality and tonal superiority.
With a passionate dedication to Gibson guitar heritage, the Gibson Custom Shop team have created an incredibly authentic reissue of the 1958 Les Paul Standard with stunning attention to detail.

Lightweight Mahogany has been used for the body of the 1958 Les Paul Standard reissue. Keeping to the original spec, the body features no weight relief and gives you that classic, weighty playing feel.
Atop the Mahogany back and fitted the traditional way with hide glue is a plain Maple top with an elegant arch.
The signature single cutaway of the Les Paul guitar not only looks great but provides great access to the upper fret for easy guitar solo performance.
Attached to the body with an old school long tenon and hide glue fit is a solid Mahogany neck.
It has a round, chunky C-shape profile for a substantial grip in your hand and extra leverage for bending.

Atop the neck, fitted again with hide glue, is a traditional Rosewood fretboard. This fretboard features a 12" radius and Historic Gibson narrow/tall frets which offer classic playability and extremely easy bends while getting more of the Rosewood fingerboard's character in the tone.
Aged cellulose nitrate trapezoid inlays give the Gibson 1958 Les Paul Standard reissue a suitably vintage and beautifully aged appearance.
Giving the Gibson 1958 Les Paul Standard reissue its authentic, '59 Les Paul voicing is a set of two Custombucker Alnico III humbucking pickups.

Featuring great looking, authentic profile nickel silver pickup covers, these humbuckers have been meticulously designed for faithful tone reproduction and are unpotted to give you that old school, raw performance.
A three-way Switchcraft pickup selector allows use of either pickup individually or both at once.

Making sure the authentic looks, feel and performance continues through into the controls, they feature butyrate gold top hat knobs along with CTS 500K audio taper potentiometers and paper-in-oil capacitors.
Completing the great look and performance of the 1958 Les Paul Standard reissue is its nickel finished hardware.
On the body, you'll find a no-wire ABR-1 bridge with nickel-plated brass saddles and a lightweight aluminium stop bar.
Together, this hardware delivers precise intonation, increased sustain and fantastic tuning stability.
Look to the headstock and you'll find Kluson tuning machines, just like you'd find on the original 50s Les Paul guitars, offering old-school-cool looks and secure tuning.
Owning a Gibson Custom Shop guitar is a full experience and as such, it comes with a number of fantastic additional items.
First and foremost is a Lifton reissue 5-latch guitar case with its classic brown and pink colouring in keeping with the era-correct vibe.
You will also receive a Gibson custom switchplate medallion along with a historic black plastic cover in the case.

There's also a certificate of authenticity booklet for added collectable value and a set of Historic Reissue hang tags to complete the authentic 1950s experience of owning the '58 Les Paul Standard reissue.

First appearing in 1958, the Gibson ES-335 DOT set an incredible standard for semi-acoustic guitars.
Over 60 years later, the world still craves that classic Gibson ES tone and style which this Gibson ES-335 delivers in spades.
The body gives you that classic Gibson ES-335 style with its double cutaway shape granting easy access to the higher frets.
Made from a 3-ply maple/poplar/maple combination and featuring spruce bracing, the Gibson ES-335's body is extremely resonant.
Complementing the striking Sixties Cherry colour of this semi-acoustic guitar is the single-ply cream body binding.
Furthermore, with its breathable gloss nitrocellulose lacquer finish, just like the old models, this Gibson ES-335 will age beautifully.
Attached to the body is a mahogany neck with a rounded "C" shape profile for comfortable playability.
A traditional rosewood fretboard with 22 highly playable medium jumbo frets sits atop the neck.
Giving you the classic Gibson ES-335 tone that is so well loved after six decades are a set of Calibrated T-Types humbucking pickups.
These pickups are paired with a hand-wired control assembly with 500K potentiometers and orange drop capacitors for fantastic performance.
A toggle switch allows you to select between the two pickups or use both at once.
Furthermore, each pickup as its own dedicated volume and tone controls so you can get the sound just right between the two.
Completing this brilliantly crafted instrument, the Gibson ES-335 is kitted out with high quality hardware throughout.
p on the headstock, there are six Vintage Deluxe tuners with keystone buttons providing precise, secure tuning and old-school style.
Down on the body, backed up by an aluminium stop bar is an ABR-1 Tune-O-Matic bridge.
Since 1954, the ABR-1 Tune-o-Matic bridge has boasted the perfect marriage of simplicity and functionality.
Slotting directly into the Gibson ES-335's body, the ABR-1 bridge features a separate stud and thumbwheel.
As a result, you get a firm seating for your strings and you can easily fine tune your intonation and string height in no time.
Furthermore, with this bridge garnering a great union between your strings and the Gibson ES-335's body, you get increased sustain.
The Gibson ES-335 comes to you in a hard shell case and includes a Gibson accessory kit for you to take care of your new Gibson guitar.

Shortly afterwards he begain using his first ESP guitar (an MS220 Explorer) and so a legend was born.

The Snakebyte is the result of one of James's more recent collaboration with ESP. Featuring a mahogany body finished in black satin, a modified "Explorer" shape, set neck with ebony fingerboard, locking tuners and tailpiece, and James Hetfield's very own EMG JH pickup set, this guitar is an absolute must for musicians wanting to recreate that classic metal sound that helped to completely redefine the genre.
Rock Solid Construction

James Hetfield's love of the classic Explorer guitar is no secret, in fact it's the guitar that he's most associated with using. The unique looks and severe angles of the instrument help it to stand out from the crowd, and the Snakebyte continues in this tradition. Featuring some slight alterations to the more traditional Explorer shape, the Snakebyte was created based on James' own original design. The slightly shorter (24.75" scale) neck makes for more comfortable playing and easier bends, whilst the 22 XJ Fret ebony fingerboard sports a gorgeous snake inlay at the 12th fret, adding a bit of extra class to the satin black finish and black features of the instrument.
The Neck

The Thin "U" contour makes those rip-roaring shred-fests and riff-heavy masterpieces that bit more accessible, and the ebony fretboard makes for the perfect finishing touch, accurately matching the the body and headstock colours.
The Pickups

During 2009 James Hetfield approached the president of EMG Pickups with an idea: he wanted them to construct him a new pickup set that helped capture the clarity and punch of a passive pickup, whilst retaining that legendary active tone that drew him to EMG in the first place - and thus the EMG JH "Het" pickup set was born. Both pickups were patterned after the EMG 81/60 combination that James had used for 30 years, whilst at the same time being a completely new kind of monster.

The JH-N (Neck pickup) comes with individual ceramic poles and bobbins that feature a larger core and are taller than the classic EMG-60, giving you plenty of attack, a higher output and a fuller low end in the neck position.

The JH-B (Bridge pickup) uses the same kind of core as the JH-N but has steel pole pieces, unlike the 81 that uses bar magnets, giving you that familiar tight attack with less inductance for a cleaner low end.

The strings-through-body design of the bridge enhances sustain so the American Original '70s Telecaster will really sing.

newOverview.overviewBody: Jackson JS Series RR Minion JS1X, a powerful guitar in a small package, seen here in a show-stealing Neon Green
With the JS Series, Jackson give us a series of great electric guitars with awesome Jackson tone, looks and playability but at a great value price to match.
Making for an excellent first guitar, the RR Minion JS1X has the looks of a much higher end instrument and will certainly stand out on stage.

Making it perfect for younger people or those who require a smaller guitar, the JS Series RR Minion JS1X has been made to a 2/3 scale and for those that usually play full size guitars, since the RR Minion JS1X features the high-quality build, sound and features you’d expect from Jackson guitars, it even works great as a travel guitar.
The striking V-shaped body of the guitar has been crafted from Poplar and really stands out compared to your standard electric guitars.
A Maple neck has been bolted on and it features graphite reinforcement rods making for an extra secure build while guarding against warping.

Atop the neck is a 12” radius, brand new Amaranth fretboard (often referred to as Purpleheart) that features 24 jumbo frets along with classic Jackson sharkfin position inlays helping you to find your way around.
Giving the RR Minion its powerful voice that simply defies its diminutive stature is a set of Jackson high output humbucking pickups.
Found in both the neck and bridge position, these pickups give you a tough and beefy sound, great for playing heavier styles of music.
A three-position blade allows you to choose how you would like to use the pickups – the bridge or neck pickup individually or a combination of the two.
Keeping things simple so you can get the perfect the sound with ease, two knows allow you to adjust the overall tone and volume of your output.
At the headstock are six high quality Jackson sealed die-cast tuning machines allowing for quick and precise tuning of your strings.
Down on the body is a 6-saddle string-through-body hardtail bridge with block saddles, keeping your strings aligned and allowing for perfect intonation.
Being of the JS Series, the RR Minion JS1X is a fantastic guitar that comes with the sound, style and playability that Jackson guitars are famous for but at a very accessible price.

Its great value price along with its playability and 2/3 scale sizing means the JS1X is a perfect electric guitar for beginners or anyone that requires a smaller guitar without compromising on quality.
